Intermediate operations.

Intermediate operations are the ones that transform one stream into another, and they are all lazy. Calling one simply records that the operation should happen; nothing actually runs until a terminal operation starts pulling elements through the pipeline.

The ones you will use constantly are these. Filter keeps only the elements that match a predicate. Map transforms each element into something else. Flat-map flattens nested streams, which we will come back to. Distinct removes duplicates. Sorted sorts, either naturally or by a comparator you supply. Limit and skip take or drop a prefix of the stream. And peek lets you inspect elements as they flow past, which is strictly for debugging, not for real logic.

The canonical pipeline is filter, then map, then collect: start from a collection, keep the even numbers, square each one, and gather the results into a list. The one that trips people up is the difference between map and flat-map. Map is one-to-one: each input element becomes exactly one output element. Flat-map is for when each element expands into a whole stream of its own, and you want all of those flattened together into a single stream. Splitting each line of text into its words, and getting back one flat stream of all the words, is the classic example.
